Reference:
https://kind.sigs.k8s.io/docs/user/loadbalancer/ 

In a Kind (Kubernetes-in-Docker) cluster, a LoadBalancer service will stay in Pending because Kind doesn’t have a built‑in cloud load balancer. 
You need to deploy a load balancer implementation like MetalLB to assign external IPs to your service.

LoadBalancer type services rely on a cloud provider (AWS ELB, Azure LB, GCP LB) to provision an external IP.
Kind runs Kubernetes inside Docker containers, with no cloud provider integration.
That’s why your service shows:
Code
foo-service   LoadBalancer   10.96.98.103   <pending>
The cluster allocated a cluster IP (10.96.98.103), but the external IP is <pending>

Install MetalLB in your Kind cluster:
kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/metallb/metallb/v0.13.10/config/manifests/metallb-native.yaml

Configure an IP address pool that MetalLB can use:
------------ metallb-config.yaml --------------
apiVersion: metallb.io/v1beta1
kind: IPAddressPool
metadata:
  namespace: metallb-system
  name: default-address-pool
spec:
  addresses:
  - 172.18.255.200-172.18.255.250   # Example range inside your Docker network
---
apiVersion: metallb.io/v1beta1
kind: L2Advertisement
metadata:
  namespace: metallb-system
  name: default
---------------------------------------------------
kubectl apply -f metallb-config.yaml
kubectl get svc foo-service
% kubectl get svc | grep -i foo
foo-service               LoadBalancer   10.96.98.103    172.18.255.200   5678:32379/TCP                                                                     49m


---------- To access the app using Load Balancer -------
On a seperate terminal, execute:-
kubectl port-forward svc/foo-service 5678:5678
Then curl,
curl localhost:5678
--------------------

